226. et ipse, after cui, is irregular but quite natural.

227. haud nescia rerum, ‘knowing all' (quite general, like the Latin). She was a goddess in a crowd of men: they believed idle rumours, she ‘knew all.’

229. pro cunctis talibus, ‘for all these heroes.'

231. omnes, predicate, ‘are all.'

232. fatales manus, ‘those hosts of fate.' For (in V111th book) Vergil tells us how Etruria rose against its cruel king Mezentius, who fled to the protection of Turnus. Preparing to war against Turnus, they were withheld by the augur, who announced that a foreigner must lead them to battle (externos optate duces). This prophecy was fulfilled by the arrival of Aeneas, and it is to this that Iuturna is scornfully and ironically alluding.
